<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="aa-section-earth-subsection-k" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Expanding the total derivative of <m>\hat{k}</m></title>

    <p>
        As we did for <m>\hat{j}</m> in <xref ref="aa-section-earth-subsection-j" text="type-global" />,
        we split <m>\hat{k}</m> into its component parallel to the disk at latitude <m>\phi</m>.
    </p>

   <p>
        <md>
            \hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and its component perpendicular to the disk
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \hat{k} \, \sin{\phi}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        The component of <m>\hat{k}</m> perpendicular to the disk,
        <m>\hat{k} \, \sin{\phi}</m>,
        behaves like <m>\hat{k}</m> for the turntable:
        Its orientation does not change no matter where it is placed in the plane of the disk
        or at what height it is placed above or below the disk
        and no matter the angle through which the disk rotates.
        Consequently,
        we only need to consider the component  of <m>\hat{k}</m> parallel to the disk,
        <m>\hat{j} \, \sin{\phi}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
        While there is no equivalent derivation for the turntable for <m>\hat{k}</m>,
        this is similar to the <m>\hat{j}</m> derivation
        except that <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m> points outward away from the center of the disk
        rather than inward toward the center of the disk.
    </p>

    <p>
        The following derivation follows that for the turntable for <m>\hat{j}</m>,
        with <m>\hat{j}</m> replaced by <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m>.
        Only the most pertinent steps are reproduced,
        since the reader can refer to
        <xref ref="aa-section-turntable-subsection-j" text="custom">the corresponding turntable derivation</xref>
        for all steps.
    </p>

    <p>
        To evaluate <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial \lambda}</m>,
        we consider the change in <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m>'s orientation
        when its anchoring point is fixed to the edge of the disk
        and sweeps through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m> over time <m>\delta t</m>,
        as shown in <xref ref="aa-earth-k-start" text="type-global" /> below.
        <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> is the initial position of <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m>,
        and <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m> is the final position of <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m> after time <m>\delta t</m> has passed
        and it has swept through angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="aa-earth-k-start">
        <caption>
            North polar projection showing the portions of unit direction vectors
            <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m>
            at two nearby points at the edge of the disk of radius <m>R = a \cos{\phi}</m>
            from <xref ref="aa-earth-setup" text="type-global" />
            and separated by angular displacement <m>\delta \lambda</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/aa-earth-k-start.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription>
            Two portions of unit direction vectors at two nearby points
            on the edge of a circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above.
            The vectors point outward from the center of the disk.
        </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Fixing the tails of <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m> together
        in <xref ref="aa-earth-k-zoom" text="type-global" /> below
        reveals that <m>\delta \lambda</m> is the angle swept out between them
        and <m>\vec{\delta k}</m> is the vector difference between them.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="aa-earth-k-zoom">
        <caption>
        Reproduction of <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m> from <xref ref="aa-earth-k-start" text="type-global" />.
        When the tails of the vectors are fixed together,
        they are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta k}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/aa-earth-k-zoom.png" width="40%">
        <shortdescription>
            Two portions of unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
            and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
        </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Reproducing <xref ref="aa-earth-k-start" text="type-global" />
        with the tail of <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m>
        and <m>\vec{\delta k}</m> additionally included
        in <xref ref="aa-earth-k-end" text="type-global" /> below makes these relationships even clearer.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="aa-earth-k-end">
        <caption>
        Reproduction of <xref ref="aa-earth-k-start" text="type-global" />
        with the tail of <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> fixed to the tail of <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m>.
        As shown in <xref ref="aa-earth-k-zoom" text="type-global" />,
        <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m> are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m>
        and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta k}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/aa-earth-k-end.png" width="60%">
        <shortdescription>
            Two portions of unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
            on the edge of a circular disk rotating counter-clockwise about its center viewed from above.
        </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Again, we can use the arc length formula to approximate <m>|\vec{\delta k}|</m>,
        and we can take advantage of the fact that,
        since <m>\hat{k}</m> is a unit direction vector,
        <m>|\hat{k}| = 1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            |\vec{\delta k}|
            = |\hat{k_1}| (\cos{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
            = |\hat{k_2}| (\cos{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
            = |\hat{k}| (\cos{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
            = (\cos{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        From <xref ref="aa-earth-k-end" text="type-global" />,
        we can see that as <m>\delta t \to 0</m>,
        <m>\delta \lambda \to 0</m> and <m>\vec{\delta k}</m> points to the local east,
        which coincides with the <m>\hat{i}</m> direction.
        So
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-k-final-earth" number="yes"> 
            \frac{D \hat{k}}{D t}
            =
            \Omega \cos{\phi} \, \hat{i}
        </md>
    </p>

</subsection>